</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#aaaaaa><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/ucaptainmeth.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Captain Meth</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(11/24/01 7:37:04 pm)</font><br>    <BR><img src=http://www.methart.com/t_meth2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Need help in improving at CG'ing...</span><hr size=1> It depends on what kind of CG'ing you want to do.  If you want more comic book/Liquid style, then I might be able to help, but Ken would know more.  If you want more of a realistic approach, Lina or Shou would be the people to check with.  But in the end you'll end up developing your own style. <p><font face="Verdana" size="2">
I moved here from Canada and they think I'm slow, eh?
<br>
<img src="http://www.methart.com/signature.jpg"></img>

<a href="http://www.methart.com"><img src="http://www.methart.com/button/methart-fire2.jpg" border="0"></a></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CCCCCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/ulinabo.showPublicProfile?language=EN>LinaBo</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>PK Angel</span><br> <font color=#336699>(11/24/01 7:44:48 pm)</font><br>    <BR><img src=http://www.linabo.50megs.com/linapic.jpg width=100 height=78></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Need help in improving at CG'ing...</span><hr size=1> Hey there, I'd be glad to help you in whatever way I can. Maybe you could post an example of what you're working on, and explain what you'd like to accomplish with it? that would give a better idea. there's a broad range of techniques in CGing, so that would help narrow the field. <p>Disclaimer: All opinions voiced by Lina may potentially be only so-much-B.S.
</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#aaaaaa><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/ukai321.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Kai321</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(11/24/01 9:32:07 pm)</font><br>    <BR><img src=http://www.namcoarcade.com/icons/icon_t4mlaw2.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Need help in improving at CG'ing...</span><hr size=1> ::deep breath::  Ok...here we go.<br>
<br>
First, I'll say that I'm starting out by doing only cel style, being a beginner CG'er (don't wanna get too complicated starting out).  Second, though it is wanted, I don't only want C&amp;C just on these pics alone.  I would like to know how I can improve in general, if u know what I mean.<br>
<br>
Anyway, here's my second ever CG *unfinished*<br>
<!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://publish.hometown.aol.com/shadikel/myhomepage/urbangirl3.jpg?mtbrand=AOL_US"><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
<br>
THIS IS NOT MY LINE ART.  Someone posted this a long time ago, and I need practice.  The light source is coming from the front, and I have done some of the main shadows.  My main problem is putting shadows on the turban and veil (covering of the mouth).<br>
<br>
And here's my first ever CG *finished*<br>
<!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://publish.hometown.aol.com/shadikel/myhomepage/polybreak2.jpg?mtbrand=AOL_US"><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
<br>
THIS IS NOT MY LINE ART EITHER, in case u couldn't tell who it's from.  How does it look?  What could I have done to improve it?<br>
<br>
All 'n' all, I think my CG'ing skills are a bit stilted.  The characters look pale and boring compared to CG'ed chars by, say, you 2, Traum, or someone else of your calibur.  I know I'm just a beginner, but I don't have the patience and want to learn ways I can improve and quick.<br>
 <p>"I got worldwide family all over the earth/ And I worry 'bout 'em all for whatever it's worth/ From the birth to the hearse, the streets, the guns burst/ Words I disperse are here to free minds/ And if mine are needy I need to feed mine" -Rakaa (aka Iriscience) of Dilated Peoples     www.dilatedpeoples.com


</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CCCCCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/utraum4.showPublicProfile?language=EN>traum4</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(11/25/01 7:41:45 am)</font><br>    <BR><img src=http://traum4.trsqr.net/46060.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Need help in improving at CG'ing...</span><hr size=1> ^_^ I guess I make myself known good. =)<br>
<br>
I'd suggest experimenting. Personally I think cel style is harder than the smooth airbrushed style.. at least it helps a lot if you've airbrush shaded before... I started with airbrush and definitely consider it easier, cel style done good is a lot more dramatic though.<br>
<br>
But don't choose cel because you THINK airbrushing is difficult. =)<br>
<br>
Your pics would need larger areas of shadows in general, and there's very few highlights. ...I personally consider cel highlights one of the hardest things in CG.. because they are rarely near the lines like shadows are, you really have to think about their positioning.. <p><a href="http://www.geocities.com/iv4rt/"><img src="http://www.traum4.homestead.com/files/banner_s2.gif"></a></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/utraum4.showPublicProfile?language=EN>traum4</A> at: 11/25/01 7:43:02 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#aaaaaa><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/ucaptainmeth.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Captain Meth</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(11/25/01 10:23:34 am)</font><br>    <BR><img src=http://www.methart.com/t_meth2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Need help in improving at CG'ing...</span><hr size=1> Hmm...  I wouldn't have made the light source coming from directly in front of her...  That makes the task A LOT more difficult especially where that veil is concerned.  But when I use cuts in my cell style, i like to use a lot of them so that there's more of a transition between light and dark.  This is <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.methart.com/art/premarvelsuperheros.jpg">my latest piece</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> with the best examples of that.  You have to know exactly where the highest part of a certain area in question is because that will have the most highlight.  One huge thing you can use to your advantage especially where cuts are concerned is to learn the pen tool!!!  Learn it inside and out and how to use it.  You will save yourself a lot of time and stress if you can learn how to use it.  I don't know what I'd do without it.  If you don't know how to use it, an excellent tutorial can be found <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.designsbymark.com/pstips/basic_pentoola.shtml">here</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->.  Hope some of that stuff helps. <p><font face="Verdana" size="2">
I moved here from Canada and they think I'm slow, eh?
<br>
<img src="http://www.methart.com/signature.jpg"></img>

<a href="http://www.methart.com"><img src="http://www.methart.com/button/methart-fire2.jpg" border="0"></a></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CCCCCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/ufutura2001.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Futura2001</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/anim_1.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(11/25/01 10:58:35 am)</font><br>    <BR><img src=http://home.att.net/~polysin/Futura_Copy.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Need help in improving at CG'ing...</span><hr size=1> My best advice for you as I do not know your style yet...<br>
NEVER use a grey to shade!! Grey is an evil color that can be replaced with brown and ochre shades, which will improve your piece because we never a grey see in real life shading.  All good CGers know this and stay far away from greys.  Until I think of something else...<br>
Futura <p>1981, China:  54 people flocked to a rickety bridge on the yang-tzee river too watch a girl attempting to commit suicide who had jumped off the bridge.  The bridge broke, killing all 54 people.  The girl was later rescued and lived.</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#aaaaaa><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/ulinabo.showPublicProfile?language=EN>LinaBo</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>PK Angel</span><br> <font color=#336699>(11/25/01 12:08:09 pm)</font><br>    <BR><img src=http://www.linabo.50megs.com/linapic.jpg width=100 height=78></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Need help in improving at CG'ing...</span><hr size=1> I would start with an easy lightsource. I always find that the easiest is from the front and slightly above (in the case of most character, that are usually facing the viewer), because it's easier to work with the contours of the body, and it's something we generally understand better (considering that we live with the sun above us all our lives)<br>
<br>
Cell-style, airbrush, whatever you choose, I suggest experimenting by painting rough highlights (blobs, pretty much. don't bother refining them for now) on areas to get an idea of where things should go. eventually you'll develop an eye for what looks right. That's about all I could tell you, because I barely know anything about cell-style (though I need to learn) <p>Disclaimer: All opinions voiced by Lina may potentially be only so-much-B.S.
</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CCCCCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/ukai321.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Kai321</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(11/25/01 4:42:41 pm)</font><br>    <BR><img src=http://www.namcoarcade.com/icons/icon_t4mlaw2.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Need help in improving at CG'ing...</span><hr size=1> Thanks alot guys-<br>
<br>
Traum-  I will try experimenting, maybe even try new styles (when I feel ready)<br>
<br>
Meth-  I'm gonna check out ur links right now<br>
<br>
Futura- Though, it may look like it, I don't think I shaded with many greys (except for the &quot;black or grey&quot; looking colors).  What I did do for all colors was choose a darker version of it.  I can see what ur talking about and I'll try and follow your advice. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START >D --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/grin.gif ALT=">D"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
LinaBo-  I'm gonna try and do exactly what u said next time I do a CG.  Thanks for the advice! <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :D --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/happy.gif ALT=":D"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
